[
  {
    "cluster_id": "C004",
    "title": "runRealDeploy stdout/stderr handlers split chunks naively, splitting log lines that straddle reads",
    "file": "mcp/server/src/probes/manifest.ts",
    "line_ranges": [
      "121-184",
      "144-184",
      "134-142",
      "105-112",
      "129-132"
    ],
    "agreement_count": 1,
    "reviewers": [
      3
    ],
    "max_severity": "high",
    "min_severity": "low",
    "disputed_severity": true,
    "categories": [
      "error-handling"
    ],
    "recommendations": [
      "Add `child.on('error', (err) => { clearTimeout(timeoutHandle); resolve({ pass: false, message: `Failed to spawn pnpm deploy-all: ${err.message}`, logs }); });` immediately after the spawn call. Consider also surfacing a dedicated warning kind (e.g. `preflight-deploy-spawn-error`) so the skill can distinguish 'pnpm missing' from 'deploy ran and timed out'.",
      "Capture the exit code, include it in logs (`logs.push(`[deploy-all] exited with code ${code}`)`), and treat any non-zero exit as a distinct failure class — possibly a new `preflight-deploy-exit-nonzero` warning that surfaces the code alongside the captured logs. At minimum stop ignoring the code with `_code`.",
      "Maintain a small per-stream buffer: keep the trailing partial line, prepend it to the next chunk, and only push completed lines. Flush the residual buffer on close.",
      "Either thread the options through (e.g. read them from a module-level slot the harness sets via withDeployStub, or accept them as a parameter to runStubDeploy that the executor passes from a context object) or drop the unused parameters from the harness fixture signature. The current shape pretends to be configurable.",
      "Schedule a SIGKILL escalation a few seconds after the SIGTERM: `setTimeout(() => { try { child.kill('SIGKILL'); } catch {} }, 5000)`. Track whether close has fired and clear that timer in the close handler."
    ],
    "descriptions": [
      "The Promise in runRealDeploy only registers 'close' on the child. If spawn fails synchronously (e.g. EACCES) or asynchronously (the most common case on macOS/Linux is ENOENT when pnpm is on PATH at probe time but vanishes by the time the child actually executes — also possible if the spawned binary lacks +x), Node emits an 'error' event on the ChildProcess and never emits 'close'. With no 'error' listener, two things happen: (1) the promise never resolves, and (2) Node may treat the unhandled 'error' as an uncaught exception in some versions. The 7-minute timeoutHandle eventually calls child.kill() on a child that already failed, then close still doesn't fire, so the executor stays pending until the test runner / MCP transport gives up.",
      "The close handler signature is `(_code: number | null) => {}` — the underscore prefix and lack of any subsequent reference indicate the exit code is intentionally discarded. After close, the executor unconditionally enters the manifest re-probe loop regardless of whether the deploy actually succeeded. If `pnpm deploy-all --quick` exits with code 1 (e.g. compile failure inside the sandbox), the only signal the student gets is 'manifest still unreachable after 3 attempts' — a downstream symptom, not the actual root cause. The deploy logs are present in the response but the categorical 'this deploy command failed' bit is lost.",
      "Each `data` event runs `chunk.toString().split('\\n').filter(l => l.length > 0)` and pushes results into `logs`. There's no buffer for incomplete lines: if a Buffer arrives containing 'Error: cou' and the next contains 'ld not connect to localhost:9009\\n', logs will contain two entries 'Error: cou' and 'ld not connect to localhost:9009', neither of which greps cleanly. The contract test T-144 sends pre-formed lines so it doesn't catch this; real pnpm deploy output absolutely does straddle chunk boundaries.",
      "The harness's `withDeployStub({ exitCode, exposeManifest })` accepts these inputs but they're never plumbed through. `runStubDeploy()` returns hardcoded `{ pass: false, message: '[stub] deploy-all ran but manifest is not up. Run: pnpm down to clean up.', logs: [...] }` — the harness fixture's `exposeManifest: true` (used to model the happy E-008-stub path) silently has no effect, and `exitCode: 1` cannot be exercised at all. T-155 happens to want pass:false, so cycle-3 tests stay green; future scenarios wanting a stubbed pass:true path are blocked.",
      "On timeout, `child.kill()` (default SIGTERM) is called and the executor relies on the close event firing. A child that traps or ignores SIGTERM (pnpm itself doesn't, but a misbehaving deploy script run by pnpm could) won't exit, close won't fire, and the promise never resolves. Combined with R3-001 (no error handler), the failure modes for the deploy executor 'never resolve' are: spawn error before exec, child traps SIGTERM, child closes stdio without emitting close (rare but real on detached children)."
    ],
    "impacts": [
      "Real-mode deploy remediation can hang the entire MCP request for 7 minutes on a misconfigured pnpm, masquerading as a deploy timeout. The student sees 'Deploy timed out after 420000ms' when the actual error was 'pnpm not found'. T-157 is correctly deferred to Phase F today, but Phase F will reproduce this hang under the right environmental conditions.",
      "Diagnostic clarity: the surfaced warning reads as a manifest reachability problem when the underlying issue is a build/deploy failure. Skill-side messaging will guide the student toward 'pnpm down + retry' when the real fix is 'inspect the deploy logs for the compile error'. Non-trivial debugging cost on E-007-adjacent failures.",
      "Captured logs in the response are unreliable for downstream pattern matching. T-155's 'pnpm down' message generation depends on the logs being legible to the consolidator. Diagnostic noise rather than data loss.",
      "Tests that set exposeManifest:true silently get the manifest-not-up branch — a quiet contract mismatch between the harness API surface and the actual stub. Not a runtime error today; a foot-gun for cycle 4+ scenario authors.",
      "Long-tail hangs in the 7-minute-and-a-second class. Less likely than R3-001 in practice but worth tightening since the cost is small."
    ],
    "evidence": "const timeoutHandle = setTimeout(() => {\n      timedOut = true;\n      child.kill();\n    }, DEPLOY_TIMEOUT_MS);",
    "confidence_spread": [
      "high",
      "medium"
    ],
    "source_ids": [
      "R3-001",
      "R3-002",
      "R3-006",
      "R3-009",
      "R3-010"
    ]
  },
  {
    "cluster_id": "C010",
    "title": "EngineWarning's RegistryWarning member is open kind: string, not a discriminated union",
    "file": "mcp/server/src/warnings.ts",
    "line_ranges": [
      "26-31"
    ],
    "agreement_count": 2,
    "reviewers": [
      1,
      2
    ],
    "max_severity": "medium",
    "min_severity": "low",
    "disputed_severity": false,
    "categories": [
      "correctness",
      "design"
    ],
    "recommendations": [
      "Replace the open `RegistryWarning` interface with a true union of literal-kinded interfaces covering every kind registry.ts emits: `MissingPathJsonWarning | MalformedPathJsonWarning | InvalidPathJsonWarning | NoPathsDirWarning | EmptyPathsDirWarning | MissingPhasesJsonWarning | MalformedPhasesJsonWarning | InvalidPhasesJsonWarning`. Drop the orphaned PathMalformedWarning/PathsEmptyWarning/PathsMissingWarning types that mix two kinds each — they collide with the cycle 1 wire kinds.",
      "Replace RegistryWarning with an actual discriminated union of the kinds registry.ts emits (`'no-paths-dir' | 'empty-paths-dir' | 'missing-path-json' | 'malformed-path-json' | 'invalid-path-json' | 'missing-phases-json' | 'malformed-phases-json' | 'invalid-phases-json'`), drop the unused PathMalformedWarning/PathsEmptyWarning/PathsMissingWarning interfaces (or rename the active ones to match the wire kinds), so EngineWarning is a real discriminated union end-to-end."
    ],
    "descriptions": [
      "Contract A20 says `warnings.ts exports the EngineWarning discriminated union`. Most members (StateWarning, PreflightWarning, output-style warnings) are properly discriminated by literal `kind`. The RegistryWarning member, however, is declared as `{ kind: string; ...}` — an open string. registry.ts emits eight distinct kinds at runtime (`no-paths-dir`, `empty-paths-dir`, `missing-path-json`, `malformed-path-json`, `invalid-path-json`, `missing-phases-json`, `malformed-phases-json`, `invalid-phases-json`) but only three of them are listed across the typed PathMalformed/PathsEmpty/PathsMissing interfaces, and those interfaces are not actually unioned into RegistryWarning — RegistryWarning shadows them with the open type. As a result, downstream consumers of EngineWarning (e.g. start.ts) cannot narrow on `warning.kind` to a literal at compile time for any registry-emitted warning.",
      "RegistryWarning is declared as `{ kind: string; message: string; ... }` rather than a discriminated union of literal-typed variants (path-malformed, paths-empty, paths-missing, missing-path-json, malformed-path-json, invalid-path-json, missing-phases-json, malformed-phases-json, invalid-phases-json). Because RegistryWarning is a member of the EngineWarning union and accepts any string for `kind`, every EngineWarning effectively reduces to `{ kind: string; message: string }` at the discriminator level — narrowing such as `if (w.kind === 'state-corrupt')` no longer reliably narrows away other variants. The narrower interfaces declared above it (PathMalformedWarning, PathsEmptyWarning, PathsMissingWarning) are dead code: registry.ts pushes plain object literals typed as RegistryWarning rather than those interfaces, and the literal kinds those interfaces use (`path-malformed` etc.) don't actually appear in the runtime wire output (registry emits `malformed-path-json`, `empty-paths-dir`, `no-paths-dir`)."
    ],
    "impacts": [
      "Wire format is preserved character-for-character (T-174 passes), so cycle 1+2 fixtures stay green. But the type-level discrimination promise of A20 is violated for the registry slice of the union — exhaustive switch/match constructs over EngineWarning silently degrade for registry kinds. Any future cycle that wants `assertNever`-style exhaustiveness on EngineWarning will not catch a missing registry kind.",
      "Defeats the stated goal of A20 — a 'unified discriminated union'. Future code that switches on EngineWarning.kind cannot exhaustively check; the consolidator/cycle-4 caller will silently lose cases. The dead PathMalformedWarning/PathsEmptyWarning/PathsMissingWarning interfaces also create reader confusion: they look authoritative but are never instantiated."
    ],
    "evidence": "export interface RegistryWarning {\n  kind: string;\n  message: string;\n  path?: string;\n  dir?: string;\n}",
    "confidence_spread": [
      "high"
    ],
    "source_ids": [
      "R1-003",
      "R2-001"
    ]
  },
