    ],
    "descriptions": [
      "manifest.ts mixes two distinct responsibilities: (a) a passive read-only probe (`probeSandboxManifestReachable`, ~20 LOC) and (b) a non-trivial subprocess executor (`runDeployRemediation`, `runStubDeploy`, `runRealDeploy`, ~140 LOC) that spawns processes, manages timeouts, captures logs, and re-probes. The contract names this as 'the deploy executor lives in this file' but doing so makes manifest.ts the only probe file that owns active state-changing behavior. Every other probe file is a single ~20-50 LOC pure check; manifest.ts is ~185 LOC with two unrelated public surfaces. The file boundary obscures that the deploy executor is callable by the tool handler independent of the probe's pass/fail outcome, and the colocation forces the tool handler (`runPreflightProbe.ts`) to import `runDeployRemediation` from `probes/manifest.js` — leaking the probe abstraction."
    ],
    "impacts": [
      "Future maintainers reading probes/manifest.ts have to mentally separate 'is this part of the probe or part of the executor?'. Tests that mock the manifest probe accidentally widen their reach to the executor (and vice-versa). The asymmetry — 7 probe files at ~30 LOC and one at ~185 LOC — is a code-smell signal that the boundary is wrong."
    ],
    "evidence": "export async function runDeployRemediation(\n  action: ShellAction,\n  checkPrecondition: PreconditionChecker,\n  opts: { spawn?: typeof spawn } = {},\n): Promise<DeployRemediationResult> {",
    "confidence_spread": [
      "high"
    ],
