    "cluster_id": "C005",
    "title": "checkManifest fetch has no timeout — blocked port can hang the probe",
    "file": "mcp/server/src/probes/manifest.ts",
    "line_ranges": [
      "15-22"
    ],
    "agreement_count": 1,
    "reviewers": [
      3
    ],
    "max_severity": "medium",
    "min_severity": "medium",
    "disputed_severity": false,
    "categories": [
      "error-handling"
    ],
    "recommendations": [
      "Use `fetch(MANIFEST_URL, { signal: AbortSignal.timeout(5000) })` (Node 20.3+) or a manual AbortController. Same hardening on each of the three retry calls. The catch block already maps any rejection to `false`, so adding a timeout is non-breaking."
    ],
    "descriptions": [
      "`fetch(MANIFEST_URL)` is called with no AbortSignal and no `signal: AbortSignal.timeout(N)`. The contract for probe #7 says 'short connect timeout'. On a healthy machine a refused localhost connection rejects fast (good), but on a host where port 9009 is bound by something hung (e.g. a stuck deploy from a previous run, a misconfigured docker-proxy holding the port open without responding), the fetch will hang for the OS default — Node's undici defaults can be tens of seconds. Combined with the post-deploy re-probe loop (3 attempts), that's potentially 3 × default_fetch_timeout of hang per remediation."
    ],
    "impacts": [
      "Probe latency unbounded; under E-007-adjacent conditions the MCP request can stall the skill for an unbounded time. The deploy executor's 7-minute timeout doesn't cover the post-spawn re-probe phase since each fetch is independent."
    ],
    "evidence": "const response = await fetch(MANIFEST_URL);",
    "confidence_spread": [
      "high"
    ],
    "source_ids": [
      "R3-005"
    ]
  },
