      "Either (a) update T-061 to spy on FileHandle.prototype.sync (or the open-spy returned handle's sync method, mirroring T-164's pattern) and remove the redundant fs.fsyncSync, or (b) drop T-061 in favor of T-164 + a new ordering test that uses the handle path. The current shape — production code carrying a comment 'this exists only to please the spy' — is the cleanest example of test-driving-impl in the cycle."
    ],
    "descriptions": [
      "After the A18 rewrite to `fsPromises.open(tmpPath, 'r+') → handle.sync() → handle.close()`, the implementation also calls `fs.fsyncSync(handle.fd)` between handle.sync() and handle.close(). The inline comment admits this is 'redundant but required for T-061's fs.fsync* spy ordering assertion' — handle.sync() does not route through the JS-level fs.fsync export, so the legacy T-061 ordering spy needed a second sync. The contract A18 specified the durability sequence as open → sync → close → rename; it did not call for an extra fsyncSync, and carrying one in production code purely so a regression test can observe it leaks test concerns into the implementation.",
      "saveState calls `await handle.sync()` then immediately calls `fs.fsyncSync(handle.fd)`. The inline comment explains: 'Redundant but required for T-061's fs.fsync* spy ordering assertion.' This is a smell in two directions: (a) production code has a no-op syscall whose only justification is a test from cycle 2 still asserting that path, and (b) the comment confirms the cycle-2 fix bundle (C002+C007+C009+C027) was incomplete — the migration to FileHandle.sync() should have updated T-061 to spy on the new path rather than keep the old fs.fsyncSync call alive.",
      "After `await handle.sync()` (which already calls fdatasync/fsync under the hood), the implementation also runs `fs.fsyncSync(handle.fd)` with the comment 'Redundant but required for T-061's fs.fsync* spy ordering assertion.' This couples production durability code to test-spy mechanics. Concretely: if `handle.sync()` rejects, the finally still runs `handle.close()` (good), but if the redundant `fs.fsyncSync` throws (e.g. EBADF on an unusual filesystem, or after handle.sync fails to actually flush), the saveState rejection masks the original sync error. Errors from the redundant call shadow the more useful errors from the FileHandle path. The comment itself signals 'this is here for the test, not for correctness' — that's a maintenance smell.",
      "saveState now calls handle.sync() AND fs.fsyncSync(handle.fd) back-to-back. The comment is explicit: 'Redundant but required for T-061's fs.fsync* spy ordering assertion.' This is a tests-vs-impl smell — the production code has an extra syscall solely to make a cycle-2 spy pass after the cycle-3 rewrite to FileHandle. T-061 spies on fs.fsync / fs.fsyncSync / fs.fdatasync but not on FileHandle.prototype.sync, so the cycle-3 idiomatic path (just handle.sync()) doesn't satisfy the cycle-2 ordering test. The implementer chose to keep both calls instead of updating T-061 to spy on FileHandle.sync."
    ],
    "impacts": [
      "Two consecutive fsyncs on the same fd cost a second disk-flush per saveState. On NVMe this is sub-ms; on slow disks or networked FS it is observable. More importantly, the carry-forward couples future state.ts edits to a test detail that should have been migrated when the FileHandle pattern landed.",
      "Two real-world consequences: the redundant sync executes a second blocking flush per saveState (negligible perf, but non-zero), and any future maintainer reading state.ts has to grok why a Node API is called after its modern replacement. More importantly, the pattern signals 'tests dictate production shape' which is the inverse of what TDD should produce.",
      "Diagnostic clarity loss when sync genuinely fails on disk. Future maintainers seeing the redundant call may delete it (correctly) and break T-061. Conversely they may add a third fsync to satisfy a future spy. The cycle 2 carry-forward fix is real (the FileHandle is now from an 'r+' open, which addresses C002+C027) but the rewrite is half-done.",
      "Low correctness impact — the redundant fsync is a no-op overhead. But it means T-061 is not enforcing what its name claims (writeFile→fsync→rename ordering on the underlying fd) — it is enforcing a legacy syscall pattern that the cycle-3 contract explicitly rewrote away from. Future readers will be confused why the code calls sync twice; the answer 'to satisfy T-061' is unsatisfying."
    ],
    "evidence": "  try {\n    await handle.sync();\n    // Redundant but required for T-061's fs.fsync* spy ordering assertion.\n    fs.fsyncSync(handle.fd);\n  } finally {\n    await handle.close();\n  }",
    "confidence_spread": [
      "high"
    ],
    "source_ids": [
      "R1-002",
      "R2-006",
      "R3-004",
      "R5-008"
    ]
